<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100534496719233></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100534496719233><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100534496719233>General Mage Stuff</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100534496719233#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=55384><span id= >Slappie</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>2 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 9th 5:29 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>    Well...I've probably done things the hard way judging by these posts, but it's been fun, so here's my 2cp.<br><br>   1)Soloing.  I do lots of soloing and grouping.  I have no preference for either, but it's pretty easy to do in close quarters situations(dungeons esp) if I'm looking for a particular item that I don't want to share with anyone else.<br><br>  2)Dueling.  Whatever the argument for Mages vs. whatever class in a duel, I give it merit.  Necros and Shamen/Druids are all pretty tough, as are Warrior/Pallies with tons of resist.  The Mage vs. Wiz argument is absurd tho IMHO.  I've never lost a duel to any wizard, even three in a row to a wizard that was 3 levels above me.  There's just too much interrupting for wizards to deal with.<br><br>  3)The pets:  I love fire pets.  I just love how you can waltz into a place and have half the floor aggro you and all you have to do is grab your trusty staff and jump in.  Which brings me to an important technique: chain healing<br><br>   If you have a fire pet that is buffed with weaps, I think it's better to chain heal it rather than chain summon.  Just a thought.  For those not aware what that is(maybe it isn't done much, as I haven't read any posts on it)at 36 I still only have two pet heal spells.  That's fine.  Simply mem both spells, and when you don't want to aggro mobs or you need to save your pet, repeatedly cast the heals, strong first, then weak.  They'll pop up at different times.  This is very good when you're low on hp or whatever situation.  I've saved myself many times when I've had that unexpected add or 3 to deal with.  Try it out, and if it doesn't work, then flame all you want.  It's just something I've picked up on.<br><br>   Another one that people probably have picked up on: Pet Kiting.  If you have a friendly Shaman around(or if indifferent, throw some pps his way..hehe)get sows for you and pet and play tag with a mob.  Even with yellows you and your fire pet can succeed with this tactic.  Simply smack a mob from long range with a cinder bolt(you've already found a place to run with no possible adds of course) As the mob is running at you nail it with a blaze or suitible DD that casts more quickly.  Quickly send your pet in and run like hell.  Your pet will beat the crap out of the mob who's obviously hell bent on ripping your limbs off.  When it turns around to finally deal with your fire elemental, whack it with another DD and run.  Repeat.  If you have no fizzles, resists, adds, and don't run out of mana, this tactic will work.  Yeah, I know.  Running into another mob is probably not a good idea while playing tag, but that's what the zone entrance is for...  :)<br>   The other pet types are nice, but I've just gotten attached to the fire pet.  Just ask any monk who's dueled a mage with a fire pet and he'll tell you that DS is no joke.  I would use air against casters mobs though, and water if you have a shammie around.<br> <br>  Last thing(and thanks for reading this lengthy post) don't neglect your melee skills.  I know this sounds silly when you see Sarnak Knights and Sabretooth Kitties doing 80+ points of damagex2 per round, but in a group that has some silly time to kill, working up your melee skills can really help when dealing with green stuff.  Example:  Najena when going for focus items.  While trapsing between the Rathyl's mage halls and the darkbone lairs, you'll have no problem at all jumping into a fray with your own DS and a staff of writhing if you know how to fight.  Yeah, I know it sounds ridiculous having a caster with a master level of 1hb, but at least you won't have to ask some newb to 'get this bat off of you somewhere'..  :)<br>   The last point is questionable under most opinions I'm sure, but I just haven't gotten a primary slot item with INT yet.(save the focus items) It's just kind of a security blanket if you're in trouble, with no mana and your pet is low on health.  Just grab your staff and duke it out.  You'll do a little damage and your pet just may have enough time to kill the mob off before your hp clock runs out.<br><br>   As for races, well I'm partial to gnomes.  INT is decent and being able to dodge a lot of hits is nice.<br><br>  Last thing for those wishing to get a newbie mage:   Have friends do it too!  When I was 8th level I went to crushbone with 4 other mages and one wizzie(he was erudite but we'll not hold that against him).  That small army is very imposing to even much more powerful mobs.  Yes, when Dvinn shows up you should still run like hell.<br><br>   Thanks for reading.  Mages rock.  That's why we get screwed with xp sometimes.  Who cares.<br><br><br>                               Slappie<br>                               36th Gnome Mage<br>                               Vaezelle<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
