<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100455280362005></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100455280362005><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100455280362005>RE: New mage with questions</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100455280362005#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=111670><span id= >Vorish</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>20 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 31st 1:26 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>1) if your pet does more than 50% of the dmg you geet half the exp, if the pet does less than 50% of the dmg, you get some proportion of the exp (not sure how much).  Now, this sounds like a big downer, but it really isn't considering that you can solo blues faster than a melee class could (maybe 50% to 100% more in the same time frame?).  In a group situation, the pet only takes like 1% of the exp, so it doesn't come into play (from everything that I've read).<br><br>2) I usually hand my pet whatever rusty weapon I pick up that will do more dmg than what the pet can hit for.  If you're hunting wisps or other critters that are magic, you'll need to summon a magic weapon like Staff of Tracing or Staff of Warding.  A pet will wield the lowest *delay* weapon that you give it (if it already has a weapon).  So you can nerf your pet by giving it a 27dly dagger when it was wielding a big 2HS 9dmg 50dly weapon.  Pets ignore the weapon's delay and always attack with a delay of 30.  After level 16, I think pets hit for magic anyway and I only give my pet a weapon if I cast and end up with on that con's blue (and is hitting for less than what he would if I gave it a staff).<br><br>3) Keep your melee skills up to date as much as possible, get in and tank for your pet to get your offense and defense skills up.  You'll need them later when a fight goes bad and you need to get that one last spell off without getting hit and interrupted.  I'm only lvl 17, but I've heard you have to give up melee after lvl 20 or 30 (too risky), but until then I'll keep training and tanking when possible.<br><br>4) I've never seen anything like that, if I cast a lvl 16 pet, I get a lvl 14-17 pet (randomly), they all seem to wield anything with aplomb, the only difference is how hard they hit without a weapon (and how often they miss a creature).  Sometimes if I really need a good pet, I'll recast a few times until I get one that cons black, yellow, or a 'risky' blue.  (Right now, for a risky blue, I try to loot a 2HS 9dmg rusty sword to help it make up the dmg deficit.)<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Vorish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Mage lvl 20<br>Corish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Cleric lvl 9</td></tr>
