	   <tr><td colspan=2>Yeah, I can't agree either.  The best part about being a mage is having the *choice* to solo or to group (I do about half and half).  <br><br>I guess the best selfish reason to group (if you need one) is that if you don't group early and make lots of friends and allies, you'll not get invited on raids when you get up in level.  I've been averaging making a new friend every day or three since I started my character, with a few players that will travel through multiple zones to come play with me.  <br><br>Sure I could play solo, but it's also a lot of fun to help melee classes take on mobs that they wouldn't risk otherwise.<br><br>So far I think druids and paladins have the most to offer as partners to a mage.  The smarter players trust me to keep my pet healthy enough that they can back off and let the pet tank for a bit when they get a little low on hps.  The less common-sense players (hero mentality) cause me to burn more often in order to take out the mob fast enough to keep them alive (and my pet ends the fight with 100% of its hp).  Druids are good because they can root-snare and even heal my pet if I'm falling behind.<br><br>The fastest pull cycle that I've seen is the druid would run out, tag a blue or black, come back, we let the pet tank while both of us meditate (healing when needed), the mob dies, loot, and immediately pull another.  (Two of us in the mino valley in SF hunting anything that was blue or black.)  About the only time we went below 80% mana was when we got a bad pull and had to actually burn the mobs down.<br>&nbsp;<br>Vorish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Mage lvl 20<br>Corish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Cleric lvl 9</td></tr>
