	   <tr><td colspan=2>I've been feeling my way around my first EQ character as a mage for about a month now and I can understand where some of the frustration can come from.  We're definitely not tanks (even fully buffed with my lvl 16 shield and armor spells, I only have about 300pts, while a Human Druid has a touch over 400pts and probably better armor).  I look at the mage class as having to win battles through better strategy.<br><br>Still, I got into my first groups back around lvl 6 or 7 (Orc Hill, entrance to Crushbone, Steamfont).  I think it depends on the zone, the server, who's around (it was usually just a bunch of us newbies who were tired of getting swarmed and who wanted someone to stand at our back).  I've found a druid partner to be a very powerful ally (and we often just let the pet tank until things get hairy).  After doing that for a few levels, I've gotten into more and more groups as I run across people that I've grouped with before.  I've also done a good bit of solo time (mainly lvl 12 and 13 because I needed to work on pet control, raise money, or my normal group partner wanted to kill things that I didn't want to sacrifice faction with yet).  It's nice having the choice of soloing or grouping.<br><br><a href="http://eq.stratics.com/content/classes/magician/magician_index.shtml" target=_new>http://eq.stratics.com/content/classes/magician/magician_index.shtml</a><br>- this has some excellent articles on group strategy, risk management in encounters<br><br>I've seen the pathing issue in Crushbone (went there right when I turned lvl 12 with my new pet).  Looked, watched my pet do the tour, decided I wasn't ready.  Having toured Blackburrow now, I've come to view keeping your pet at your side in a dungeon as just another skill to be learned.  Sure I wish Verant would add more 'train tracks' in the dungeons so my pet would have an easier time, but I'm not going to hold my breath.  So I keep an eye on my pet, and try to learn where in each dungeon it's going to have problems.<br><br>I've two views of SOW (and similar buffs like Clarity).  One is that they're very nice to have and I'll never turn one down (unless they don't SOW the pet too, then it's less useful).  But I also don't want to get dependent on those buffs for my day-to-day play since I can't buff myself and don't want to make a pest of myself by begging for them.  <br><br>So overall, I'm very happy playing a mage and learning how to play it better.<br>&nbsp;<br>Vorish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Mage lvl 20<br>Corish of Morell-Thule, High Elf Cleric lvl 9</td></tr>
